\begin_layout Standard
Insects find food and mates by navigating odor plumes that can be highly
 intermittent, with intensities and durations that vary rapidly over orders
 of magnitude.
 Much is known about olfactory responses to simple pulses and steps of odor,
 but it remains unclear how Olfactory Receptor Neurons (ORNs) detect the
 intensity and timing of natural signals, where the absence of a characteristic
 scale in the stimulus makes detection a formidable task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we propose a method by which odorant signals with naturalistic and
 Gaussian statistics can be generated in a reproducible manner, and show
 how the instantaneous flux of odorant molecules can be measured.
 By eliciting ORN responses to these stimuli, we show 
\emph on
in vivo
\emph default
