\emph default
 ORNs contribute to naturalistic sensing by using receptor adaptation and
 saturation to change their gain in response to stimulus mean and variance.
 Mean-dependent gain control followed the Weber-Fechner relation and occurred
 primarily at odor transduction, while variance-dependent gain control occurred
 both at transduction and at spiking.
 Odorant transduction and spiking generation possessed complementary kinetic
 properties, that together preserved the timing of odor encounters in ORN
 spiking despite the fact that adaptation slowed transduction.
 
